    <title>Combined summary - libconsensus assertion fails if used in multiple threads</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T19:32:08.838516+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-August/010219.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin Core and libbitcoinconsensus are planning to switch away from OpenSSL in the near future. This move is expected to help avoid issues like the one that recently occurred. Tamas Blummer, who integrated libconsensus into Bits of Proof, confirmed that it works well with their Java engine. He also reported that it is about 50% faster on a single thread. However, when executed on several threads simultaneously, an error arises due to lack of registration of thread callbacks as advised for OpenSSL. This is because OpenSSL requires access to functions that are not exported from the library.A workaround has been provided by Cory Field until they switch to the new libsecp256k1 lib for validation. The issue with OpenSSL relates to the secp256k1 curve used by Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies. Fields prepared a patch for those who may run into the issue, which was tested in Bits of Proof's stack and found to be performing well.Bitcoin Core's libconsensus has received a pull request to fix a rare bug in parallel transaction validation that could produce incorrect results. The patch has already been tested in Bits of Proof's stack and is performing well. While it may not be necessary for the next release of Core, Cory Fields believes it should be backported to the 0.10 and 0.9 series. Additionally, Corey Fields notes that Core is switching to libsecp256k1 for several reasons, including speed. However, there is no timeline for secp256k1 integration. Meanwhile, Tamas Blummer confirmed that libconsensus is working correctly within the Bits of Proof stack, as per test cases borrowed from Bitcoin Core to verify the Java implementation of the script engine. He found that the performance of libconsensus is surprisingly close to the java version.</summary>
